In this chapter it is discussed how the bash enviroment can be influenced

.1.1 Shell init files - System-wide config files

 • /etc/profile
 this file is read when the shell is invoked interactively or as sh
 Usually this file sets some shell variables and sometimes it has the umask configuration.
 and sometimes it has pointers to the /etc/inputrc or/and /etc/profile.d files

 all settings you want applied to your users' enviroment should be here

 • /etc/bashrc
 this config is bash specific, not like /etc/profile. in some cases ~/.bashrc points to this file for configuration upon login

.1.2 Individual user configuration files

 • ~/.bash_profile
 preferred config file for configuring user evn individually

 • ~/.bash_login
 specific settings only excecuted on login, this file is read in the absence of  ~/.bash_profile

 • ~/.profile
 in the absence of ~/.bash_profile and ~/.bash_login, this is read

 • ~/.bashrc
 when you open a terminal window manually, you do not have to log in. in that case, bash searches for this file

 • ~/.bash_logout
 this file contains instuctions for the logout procedure

