.2 Variables

.2.1 Types of variables

running "set" with no options will display all variables including enviroment vars.

shell variables are uppercase by convention. there are 2 types of variables.

 - global variables or enviroment variables: available in all shells. you can see the with the env or printenv commands
 - local variables: only available in the current shell.

also we can divide them by content, with the types:
 - string
 - integer
 - constant
 - array

.2.2 Creating variables

to set a variable name, use:
	VARNAME="value"
but this variable is local, so its only available for the current shell, and child processes of this shell cant access it. 
to make it available for subshells we use export, like so:
	export VARNAME="value"

.2.4 Reserved variables

bash and sh reserve a lot of variables and you cant use them, there is a list in the book

