.4. Shell expansion

after a command is split into tokens, these are expanded, there are many types of expansion and whe will mention them in the order they are performed

.4.2. Brace expansion

brace expansion is a mechanism to create arbitrary strings, they take the form of a PEAMBLE, a series of comma-separated strings and a POSTSCRIPT, with both the PREAMBLE and POSTSCRIPT being optional, an example of this is:
 sp{el,il,al}l
which is expanded into
 spill spell spall

.4.3. Tilde expansion

if a word begins with ~ , all characters up to a / (or all if there is none)
are considered a tilde-prefix.
if none of the chars in the tilde-prefix are quoted they (except ~) are treated as a login name.
if this name is NULL then it is replaced with the HOME shell variable.
if this variable is unset, then it is replaced with the home directory of the use excecuting the shell. this happens on cd ~

if the tilde-prefix is "~+" the PWD replaces it. and if it is "~-" it is replaced by OLDPWD

.4.4. Shell parameter and variable expansion

the $ char introduces parameter expansion, command sucstitution or arithmetic expansion. this is done like 
	${PARAMETER}
If the first character of "PARAMETER" is an exclamation point, Bash uses the value of the variable formed
from the rest of "PARAMETER" as the name of the variable; this variable is then expanded and that value is
used in the rest of the substitution, rather than the value of "PARAMETER" itself. This is known as indirect
expansion.

.4.5. Command substitution

this allows the standard output of a command to replace the command itself, this is done like this:
	$(command)
or like:
	`command`
this can be nested. if the substitution appears withind double quotes, wordsplitting and filename expansion are not performed on the results

.4.6. Arithmetic expansion

this allows the evaluation of arithmetic expression and substitution for the result, the form for this is:
	$((EXPRESSION))
los operadores son los mismos que en C

constantes que empiezan con 0 son considerados octales, si empiezan con 0x o 0X son hexadecimales, otros numeros toman la forma "[BASE'#']N" donde BASE es un numero entre 2 y 64, y N es el numero en esa base

.4.7. Process substitution

only supported on systems that support named pipes (FIFOs) or the /dev/fd method of naming open files. It takes the form of
	<(LIST)
or
	>(LIST)

more information on this on 8.2.3

.4.8 Word splitting
 
$IFS: Internal Field Separators, its a shell variable containing  

the shell scans the result of parameter expansion, command substitution and arithmetic expansion that did not occur within double quotes for word splitting.
the shell treats each char of $IFS as a delimiter, and splits the results scanned into words on these chars

(read the man page!!!!!!!)

.4.9 File name expansion

bash scans each word for the chars "*", "?" and "[". if one of these appears then the word is considered a pattern and is replaced by all the filenames that match the pattern.
if nullglob is disbled, if there's no matches, the word is unchanged. if nullglob is enabled, it is removed.


